title: Production of Neutrons with Protons of 22, 30, and 40 MeV in Stopping Targets of Carbon, Aluminum, Copper, Silver, Tantalum, and Lead

MeV in Stopping Targets of Carbon, Aluminum, Copper,

x4freetext: Each target was a cylinder 2.54 cm in diameter and of
thickness equal to the proton range in each material;
there was a set of six targets for each proton
NE-213 liquid scintillator encapsulated in a
cylinder of glass with inside dimensions of 4.44-cm
The plan of the measurements was to
detect and determine the energies of the neutron
following techniques were used: TOF to determine
induced pulses, and flight path of two different
lengths to cover a large neutron energy range with
good resolution. Faraday cup was used to determine
the number of incident protons during each run.
Plotted data corrections were made for dead time of
the electronics and for interactions of the neutrons
within the stopping targets. Depending on beam
intensity and neutron yield, the dead time
corrections were in the range of 5 to 15 %.
Corrections for neutron interactions were more
complex, but the results were of no greater magnitude.
Combing all errors in quadratures gives a
Reduced number of neutrons reaching the
detector due to in scattering from neighboring parts.
